     </div>
     <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA05d195n1-ptr" id="PJA05d195n1">1</a>
      <p>Most successful leader.</p>
     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA05d195n2-ptr" id="PJA05d195n2">2</a>
      <p>William Woodford of Virginia, who was wounded at Brandywine (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Francis B. Heitman, comp., &lt;i&gt;Historical Register of Officers of the Continental Army during the War of the Revolution&lt;/i&gt;, new edn., Washington, 1914. ]">Heitman, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Register Continental Army</span></span>, p. 604).</p>
     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#" id="PJA05d195n3">3</a>
      <p>Col. James Hendricks of the 1st Virginia Regiment and Col. John Brown, who distinguished himself in leading the effort to recapture Ticonderoga in September (same, p. 285; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Christopher Ward, &lt;i&gt;The War of the Revolution&lt;/i&gt;, New York, 1952; 2 vols. ]">Ward, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">War of the Revolution</span></span>, 2:523).</p>
